docs.abstract: The coronavirus disrupted lives around the world and sent the gymnast Sunisa Lee, the swimmer Rudy Garcia-Tolson, the Seattle Storm’s Breanna Stewart and the Seattle Mariners’ Kyle Lewis on unexpected journeys.
docs.snippet: The coronavirus disrupted lives around the world and sent the gymnast Sunisa Lee, the swimmer Rudy Garcia-Tolson, the Seattle Storm’s Breanna Stewart and the Seattle Mariners’ Kyle Lewis on unexpected journeys.
docs.lead_paragraph: The coronavirus pandemic had been blanketing countries and devastating populations for months by the time the American sports landscape was touched in mid-March. As positive cases were confirmed in professional athletes, leagues shut down completely, postponed entire seasons and, in the case of the Olympic and Paralympic Games, delayed culminating events until 2021.

headline.main: What These Athletes Learned From Their Pandemic Pauses
headline.print_headline: ‘2021 Has to Be Better Than 2020. I Just Know It Will Be.’

byline.original: By Matt Futterman, Juliet Macur, Talya Minsberg and James Wagner

docs.abstract: India’s cases are falling — for now.
docs.snippet: India’s cases are falling — for now.
docs.lead_paragraph: Two months ago, India looked like a coronavirus disaster zone, with nearly 100,000 new infections a day and deaths shooting up. Today, reported infections, deaths and the share of people testing positive have all fallen significantly.

docs.abstract: Readers tell us how their faith in the American ideal has fared this election season.
docs.snippet: Readers tell us how their faith in the American ideal has fared this election season.
docs.lead_paragraph: In her essay, “Don’t Give Up on America,” Marilynne Robinson describes the “deep if sometimes difficult affinity” she has for her country. At the end of a long, contentious election season, it’s not surprising that Ms. Robinson has become disillusioned with that love affair. “Resentment displaces hope and purpose the way carbon monoxide displaces air,” she writes.

headline.main: What Does It Mean to Love Your Country?

byline.original: By Rachel L. Harris and Lisa Tarchak

docs.abstract: The use of artificial intelligence and facial recognition programs may lead communities to lose trust in law enforcement, human rights experts say.
docs.snippet: The use of artificial intelligence and facial recognition programs may lead communities to lose trust in law enforcement, human rights experts say.
docs.lead_paragraph: GENEVA — Police departments across the United States have been drawn to the use of digital technology for surveillance and predicting crime on the theory that it will make law enforcement more accurate, efficient and effective. The alarming reality, United Nations human rights experts warned on Thursday, is that they risk reinforcing racial bias and abuse.

headline.main: U.N. Panel: Technology in Policing Can Reinforce Racial Bias
